<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix herbacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Only one record and apparently a very rare species in Greenland recorded only once during the 20 years when Borgen regularly collected in Paamiut. The general distribution in Europe (
<bibRefCitation author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
) is from the Temperate zone to southern Boreal and Subalpine zone up to 1700 m. The Greenland record is the northernmost known (62.00°N). Temperate, boreal, subarctic, and now also from Low Arctic zone.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Habitat and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Only one collection, with 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix herbacea" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="herbacea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix herbacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In Europe, the hosts are 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Betula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Picea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Picea" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Coniferophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Picea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
), but the associated 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are of the shrub-like kind, like 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. aurita" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="aurita">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. aurita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
